Class CWBPickerLambda

  • java.lang.Object
    • gov.usgs.anss.edgethread.EdgeLogger
      • gov.usgs.anss.edgethread.EdgeLambda

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ManagerInterfaceLambda
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    CWBFilterPicker6Lambda, CWBSubspaceDetectorLambda, TemplatePicker

    public abstract class CWBPickerLambda
extends EdgeLambda
implements ManagerInterfaceLambda
    This class provides the common data access and pick reporting from the NEIC CWB program QueryMom. A USGS generated picker, or an interface to an external picker is provided by extending this class and providing the implementation of the abstract methods. All picker threads run in real time use the PickerManager class to start up the pickers which implement this class. The PickerManager class also provides unique sequences for all pickers by providing a access to write picks into a database and the database ID is the unique sequence.

    To picker implementers, please see the abstract methods that your class need to implement when extending this class. An example is the CWBFilterPicker which implements this and causes the standard interface to all the FilterPicker library from Anthony Lomax as it was written. This allows the picker implementation to remained undisturbed by its use by the NEIC/Edge/CWB software as much as possible.

    Notes on the rather complicated startup. This class reads everything in but does not do the expensive opening of the QueryRings etc until the initial part of the run() method. Until this is done the subclass cannot use any attributes of this class until it knows that this class is done. When this class is ready it calls the "isReady()" abstract class which is the cue to that subclass to finish its startup. This complicates the constructor in the subclass to only do fast things, and then wait for the call to isReady() to trigger completing the setup now that the parent class has finished its setup. The easiest example is the value of "rate" in the parent class is not known until the parent class has completed opening its QueryRings etc. Hence the constructor of the subclass cannot use rate in the constructor but should put any setup it needs into the isReady() method. This also means isReady() should return false the constructor has comleted which depends on the constructor. A flag that sets at constructor completion or some object being not null that is built is the best bet.

    These command line options are shared by all pickers and control the realtime, DB, time segments, and JSON reporting. The actual extending class will implement its own options for things specific to that picker class. All of these options end up written into the state file which is used to pick up the real time processing. As such these parameters might be overridden by the state file if this is a continuous realtime process thread.

    The JSONDectionSender can be obtained many ways :
    1) It can be set on the creation by including the sender in the constructor arguments
    2) It can be specified on the command line here in which case this overrides and is individual to each picker
    3) It can be defined in the PickerManager either at instantiation or by static setJSONSender(). This become the sender if none of the above has set on.
    4) It can be null in which case no picks JSON messages are created.

     These command line options can only be invoked on the command line (no equivalent exists in the template file).
 switch   args    description
 -1               If present this is a segment picker, not continuous
 -nodb            If present, set DBServer and PickDBServer to "NoDB"
 -template       Specify the template file to use for this instance
 -path            The state file is written on this path, templates are all in this directory (default is ./Picker/
 -id              Set the picker ID
 -noapply         If present, the the picker is run, but the apply() function is not called

 For properties that come from a template file (separator for key#pairs is '#')  A -template file is needed
 to use a template in which case none of these switches would normally be used - the template file would set
 these parameters.  A template file can be used in two ways 1)  It contains all of these parameters including
 NSCL and is they useful for running a station, 2) the more common is to set all of these parameters except NSLC and
 invoke the picker with -c on the command line.
 Property      switch args      description
 TemplateFile -template file   ! this refers to the template manually create or from the picker table

 NSCL         -c NNSSSSSCCCLL  The channel to process, comes from the -c mostly but can be in preconfigured template
 Blocksize    -blocksize       The processing block size in seconds
 PickDBServer -db   dbURL      Set the DB where the status.globalpicks us located (used to generate ID numbers) 'NoDB' is legal
 Author       -auth author     Set the author (def=FP6)
 Agency       -agency agency   Set the agency
 Title        -t     title     A descriptive title for this instance (example FP6-RP)
 CWBIPAdrdess -h     cwb.ip    Set source of time series data (def=cwbpub)
 CWBPort      -p     port      Set the CWB port (def=2061)
 MakeFiles    -mf              If present, this instance will make files in MiniSeed from parameters.
 PickerTag    -f     pickerTag Some tag associated with the picker (def=NONE)
 OverrideTopic -topic Kafka topic The kafka topic to use when sending picks from this picker (def=null)
 JSONArgs     -json  1;2&3;4   @see gov.usgs.picker.JsonDetectionSender for details


 For properties kept in the state file :
 StartTime    -b     begintime Starting time, not valid on a segment picker
 EndTime      -e     endTIme   Ending Time
 Rate         -rt    Hz        The digit rate, else one from the time series will be used

 Here is an example template file for RayPicker version generic template for the  FilterPicker:
 note the above tags use "=" as a separator and the FilterPicker version uses "#" as its separator.  This is
 generic in that the NSCL is not present so that it can be used to run many instances with one channel per
 instance.  In this case the "-c NNSSSSSCCCLL" is on the command line.  Additionally you can see that the
 Start and End times are commented here so that they can be specified on the command line with -b and -e, similarly
 the rate could be specified on the command line but 100 Hz would be used if it was not.

 Example command : java -cp my.jar.file full.path.to.pickerclass -c USDUG--BHZ00 -b 2019/01-01 -e 2099/13/31 -template RayPick.template

 cat RayPick.template
 !Key=value                   ! for CWB Picker
 Blocksize=10                ! The processing block size in seconds
 PickDBServer=localhost/3306:status:mysql:status         ! Set the DB where the status.globalpicks and edge.picker configuration are
 Author=FP6-RP               ! Set the author (def=FP6)
 Agency=US                   ! Set the agency
 !StartTime=yyyy/mm/dd hh:mm ! begintime Starting time, not valid on a segment picker
 !EndTime=yyyy/mm/dd hh:mm   !  Ending Time
 Title=FP6-RP                 ! A descriptive title for this instance
 Rate=100.00                 ! The digit rate, else one from the time series will be used
 CWBIPAddress=localhost      ! Set source of time series data
 CWBPort=2061                ! 2061 always we hope
 Makefiles=true              ! If true, this instance will make files in MiniSeed from parameters.
 PickerTag=FP6-RP             ! Some tag associated with the picker
 !JSONArgs=                   ! see gov.usgs.picker.JsonDetectionSender for details
 !key#value                   ! for FP6 Prog Def  Comment
 bands#2.6063,0.5:2.085,1.0:1.668,1.0:1.334,1.0:1.0675,1.:0.8540,.5  ! fr,fact:fr,fact... where fr is center freq in Hz and fact is the scaling factor for thresholds
 filterWindow#0.8            ! 0.8
 longTermWindow#30.          ! 6.0
 Threshold1#8.00             ! 9.36
 Threshold2#1.00             ! 1.0
 TupEvent#20.                ! 20.
 TupEventMin#0.25            ! 1.

      • writestate

        public abstract void writestate()
                         throws java.io.FileNotFoundException,
                                java.io.IOException
        This method builds a StringBuilder of the state file parameters specific to the extending picker for key-value pairs that change over time (not things in the template) and then calls the parent writeState(StringBuilder) to actually combine and write the state file. For many pickers this will do nothing, others might record a background noise level to help the picker warmup quicker, etc. 
         public void writestate() {
   synchronized (statussb) {
     Util.clear(statussb);
     statussb.append("configfile#").append(configFile).append("\n");  // save the config file
     writeStateFile(statussb);
   }
 }
        Throws:
        java.io.FileNotFoundException - if one occurs
        java.io.IOException - if one occurs

      • setArgs

        public abstract void setArgs(java.lang.String s)
                      throws java.io.FileNotFoundException,
                             java.io.IOException
        The CWBPickerLambda handles many arguments from the state file itself. These are : Title, Starttime, Endtime, NSCL, CWBipaddress,CWBport Blocksize, Agency, Author and PickDBServer Each picker can have addition data specific to that picker. The extending class needs to define these are read the in setArgs() and provide them as a StringBuilder in the writestate() method when it calls writeStateFile of the parent class. The user can use the static statesb variable to make the state, but needs to synchronize its usage. Example : 
           public final void setArgs(String s) throws FileNotFoundException, IOException {
   try {
     BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(new StringReader(s));
     for(;;) {
       int len = Util.stringBuilderReadline(in, line);
       if(len < 0) break;
       if(line.indexOf("=") >= 0) continue;     // Its from the CWBPickerLambda part of the template
       if(line.indexOf("!") >= 0) line.delete(line.indexOf("!"), line.length());
       if(line.length() == 0) continue;
       if(line.indexOf("#") > 0) {
         Util.clear(key).append(line.substring(0, line.indexOf("#")));
         Util.clear(value).append(line.substring(line.indexOf("#")+1));
         if(Util.stringBuilderEqualIgnoreCase(key,"-dbg")) dbg=true; // User if/else if to parse all parameters
         else prt("**** Unknown tag in state file s="+line);
       }
     }
   }
   catch(IOException e) {

   }
 }
        Parameters:
        s - String with all of the state file parameters not handled by CWBPickerLambda - i.e. those for the specific picker
        Throws:
        java.io.FileNotFoundException - if one occurs
        java.io.IOException - if one occurs

      • isReady

        public abstract boolean isReady()
        indicate the picker is ready to pick. The parent class calls this when it has completed its initialization including setup of the QueryRings (where the rate is finally set) to see if the subclass is ready to have its apply() method fed data. Most pickers have a local variable called constructorDone which is set at the end of the subclass's constructor. This routine should wait for the constructor to be done, and then finish its setup in this method especially if it needs anything from the parent class. Until this is called the first time by the parent none of the attributes of the parent should be considered as set. Additionally most pickers have a "ready" boolean that is set true when the initialization is completed in this class. At that point any further calls to this method should just return this status. THe parent would normally call this class until it returns true and then never call it again. true when it is ready to run (often at the end of the constructor when all configuration is done. It sets it false in the terminate routine. Ready should not return true until the subclass instance is ready for apply() to be called. 
           public boolean isReady() {
 // if we have not reached ready state, insure the constructor is done and then complete all configs
 if(!ready && constructorDone) {
 rate = getRate();
 // here complete any setup that depends on attributes from the parent class.  The parent is not
 // fully setup until this routine is called
 // .
 // .
 ready = true;

 }
 return ready;
 }
        Returns:
        Whether all setup is completed and picker is ready.

      • parentSwitch

        public final int parentSwitch(java.lang.String arg)
        this is to help the extender class to skip over parameters handled by this class. The return is the value to add to the index interating over the args (normally variable i). If -1, then this parameter should have been handled by the extender class.
        Parameters:
        arg - Normally args[i]
        Returns:
        0 if single switch (-dbg) , 1 if switch + arg, or -1 if this is not a switch to this class.

      • pickCorrelation

        public final void pickCorrelation(JsonDetectionSender jsonSender,
                                  java.lang.String pickerType,
                                  java.util.GregorianCalendar picktime,
                                  double amplitude,
                                  double period,
                                  java.lang.String phase,
                                  double error_window,
                                  double latitude,
                                  double longitude,
                                  double depth,
                                  long originTime,
                                  double snr,
                                  double magnitude,
                                  double distance,
                                  double azimuth,
                                  java.lang.String eventType,
                                  double zScore,
                                  double threshold,
                                  java.lang.String thresholdType,
                                  double correlation)
        Create a new pick, get an ID and put int the DB with PickManager, and send info via JSON if a sender is present.
        Parameters:
        jsonSender - The json sender to use, null if none
        pickerType - Something to identify this picker type like "FP" for FilterPicker
        picktime - The time of the pick in millis
        amplitude - The amplitude of the pick - this case the correlation value
        period - The period of the pick
        phase - The phase of the pick
        error_window - The error_window of the pick in seconds
        latitude - The latitude of the reference event
        longitude - The longitude of the reference event
        depth - The depth of the reference event;
        originTime - The origin time of this event using the offset from the reference one
        magnitude - The magnitude estimate from this pick
        zScore - The zScore if one is computed -1 if not
        threshold - The threshold of the picker in correlation
        thresholdType - Normally "constant" since other methods are not use
        snr - Estimate for this picker
        distance - associated distance in degrees
        azimuth - associated azimuth in degrees
        eventType - either "blast", or "earthquake" or null
        correlation - The correlation value at this pick (not used in JSON)
